In <Cr56tt.496@undergrad.math.uwaterloo.ca> elee@undergrad.math.uwaterloo.ca (Salty Freckles) writes:

>I'm not sure if this has been brought up before or whether it is even a valid
>concern, but I was wondering about the security liabilities of having a
>nation's encryption keys stored in a central database (okay, granted it's
>two databases) under the Clipper proposal.

>From a paranoid standpoint, wouldn't the event of a database compromise at
>both sites render all Clipper devices useless as viable encryption devices?
> 
>-- 
>Gene Lee
>elee@descartes.UWaterloo.ca

I would think a *greater* compromise would be that the universe of valid
keys (at least in the early years) would be so small that a simple brute force
attack against all assigned keys could be done in a very short length of
time.


